article.description:
The New York Liberty's frontcourt players made
sure the Phoenix Mercury remained winless in New York.
article.headline: Mercury now has lost five in a row
article.linkText: New York goes inside to keep Phoenix frustrated
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Liberty's frontcourt players made sure the Phoenix Mercury remained winless in New York. Forward Tamika Whitmore scored a career-high 28 points and center Tari Phillips added a season-high 23 points to lead the Liberty over the Mercury 77-71 Monday night. Becky Hammon scored eight of her 14 points late in the game, and Teresa Weatherspoon, who along with Phillips was voted as a starter for the WNBA All-Star Game, had nine assists for the Liberty, playing for the first time in six days. ''We didn't feel like they could stop our people in the paint. Tonight was the night for the big girls,'' Weatherspoon said, directing her attention to Whitmore. ''That big bear went in and did her thing.'' Jennifer Gillom scored 25 points for Phoenix, which dropped its fifth in a row since winning June 26, when head coach Cynthia Cooper resigned and Linda Sharp took over. The defeat was the Mercury's fifth consecutive in the Garden since the WNBA began play in 1997. ''I would jump for joy if we could get a road win out of this,'' Gillom said. ''We are just struggling, but it's not all about us. Teams are having their best games against us. People are coming off the bench and having career nights against us. It's tough.'' The Mercury tied a season-high with 19 turnovers but still had a chance to win late in the second half. Adriana Moises Pinot hit a 3-pointer to cut New York's lead to 51-45 with 11:14 left, but Whitmore and Hammon took over. ''We didn't deny them the ball,'' Sharp said. ''We played behind Whitmore and she just shot the ball over us. ''Their inside game was the biggest problem. That's why we went into a zone in the second half. It was pretty effective for a while, then they got Becky Hammon in the game ... and we had to come out of the zone.'' Whitmore hit four consecutive inside baskets and Hammon followed with four quick jumpers from the outside to boost the Liberty's lead to double digits. ''That's just the way my mother taught me to play,'' Whitmore said. ''I haven't even scratched the surface yet. I'm not even close to playing my best.'' Lisa Harrison, who had 13 points, hit a 3-pointer with 1:12 left to bring the Mercury to 69-64. Gillom hit a 3-pointer with seven seconds left, but Phillips made a two free throws to seal it. ''She has that miracle water somewhere -- you've got to respect her,'' Phillips said of Gillom, who at 38 says she wants to play at least another year. ''I feel like I'm young again, for some reason,'' Gillom said. ''I want a win at Madison Square Garden, and I guess it will have to be some other season. It's like I can just never win here.'' Notes
New York won its second consecutive, only its third winning streak of the season. ... Whitmore's previous best was 21 points against Sacramento on June 13. ... Gillom's 25 points tied her season high.
